• Findings

  1. High: the temperature solve uses Conjugate Gradient on a non-symmetric matrix after the advection term
     was added. The advection contribution in step57base.cc:724 makes the operator non-symmetric, but
     step57base.cc:742 still solves it with SolverCG. That is not a valid solver choice for the assembled
     system. It may appear to work on some meshes/parameters, but it is not mathematically correct and can
     fail or behave unpredictably as the flow gets stronger or the mesh changes. This should be switched to
     GMRES/FGMRES or BiCGStab with a suitable preconditioner.
  2. Medium: the advection-diffusion discretization is plain Galerkin with no stabilization, so it is
     fragile in advection-dominated regimes. The transport term is assembled in step57base.cc:724 without
     SUPG, upwinding, or any other stabilization. For this Reynolds-number range and a sharp heated inlet,
     that is a standard source of spurious oscillations or mesh-dependent smearing. I checked the saved
     final VTKs and the temperature stayed within [0,1], so there is no obvious sign mistake, but robustness
     is still weak.
  3. Medium: the temperature-cell classification is coupled to a second DoFHandler by iterator lockstep,
     which is brittle. In step57base.cc:690, flow_cell is advanced in parallel with the temperature cell
     loop and is then used to decide both material conductivity and whether advection is active. That works
     only as long as both DoFHandlers traverse active cells in exactly the same order. It is a fragile
     hidden assumption; if traversal ever diverges, temperature cells will silently get the wrong material
     or velocity. Better to derive the material from the triangulation cell corresponding to the current
     temperature cell directly, or loop over triangulation cells and reinit both handlers from the same
     cell.
  4. Low: the thermal boundary-condition change is substantial but undocumented in code. step57base.cc:374
     now sets T=0 on 10 and 20, and step57base.cc:382 sets T=1 on inlet 60. That is physically plausible for
     “hot inflow, cold outer walls”, but it no longer matches the earlier task note in TASKS.md that phase
     one used 10 and 20 as the thermal Dirichlet boundaries with the others natural. If this was
     intentional, it should be documented because it changes the problem definition, not just the
     implementation.

  Assessment

  The core integration is mostly conceptually right. A continuous scalar temperature field on the whole mesh
  is the correct way to model perfect thermal contact, selecting conductivity by material is correct, and
  restricting the advection term to fluid cells only is also correct. I do not see an obvious sign error in
  the weak form of the advection term.

  The main correctness problem is solver choice: after adding advection, the thermal linear system is no
  longer SPD, so the current CG + SSOR path is the wrong algorithm. After that, the main weak point is
  numerical robustness: plain Galerkin advection-diffusion will be sensitive at higher Peclet numbers.